{
  "query": "What are the conservation benefits of prohibiting spearfishing in marine reserves in the Mediterranean?",
  "relevant_summary": "In the Mediterranean, prohibiting spearfishing (often alongside line fishing) in marine reserves has been associated with higher abundances of targeted fish such as European seabass and gilthead seabream after two to seven years [2672]. It has also been associated with larger sizes of European seabass in protected areas compared to fished areas over similar time frames [2672]. Comparisons between spearfished and non-spearfished areas 10\u201312 years after implementation reported differences in fish densities related to depth and/or fish size [2672]. Additionally, zones within a Mediterranean marine reserve that prohibited spearfishing saw higher commercial and recreational catches of targeted common dentex than zones allowing spearfishing and areas outside the reserve after one to three years [2672].",
  "action_ids": [
    "2672"
  ]
}

