{
  "query": "What are the effects on marine fish populations of prohibiting different types of bottom fishing gear?",
  "relevant_summary": "Prohibiting mobile bottom-towed gears dragged across the seafloor was associated with higher total fish biomass after 15 years, larger adult red mullet after 14 years, and increased abundances of long\u2011snouted seahorses after one year, though several studies reported no change in overall fish abundance, average fish weight, or species richness/diversity, and haddock recruitment and survival did not increase seven years post\u2011closure; recruitment increased for young red mullet after 14 years (2673). Prohibiting all bottom gears (mobile and static) was associated with higher numbers of larger and older cod after 15 years and improved cod growth after 5\u201315 years, while fish densities showed mixed responses, varying by species/group and environmental factors, and in some cases showed no differences after 2\u20137 years (2654).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2673",
    "2654"
