{
  "query": "What are the documented ecological outcomes of managing small-scale traditional fisheries, either through prohibition or by making them the only permitted fishing type?",
  "relevant_summary": "- Allowing only small-scale traditional (artisanal) fishing in a marine protected area zone for three years was associated with higher overall commercial catch rates for five of seven species compared to openly fished areas (2678).\n- Prohibiting all fishing with limited exceptions in marine protected areas produced mixed fish community and population responses: lower total fish species richness in some areas compared to unprotected sites; similar biomass and lower total fish density when only bait fishing was allowed; similar abundance for several rockfish species and lingcod relative to fished sites; increased cod survival inside the protected area; and frequent, prolonged use of protected habitats by some shark species, reducing likelihood of fishing mortality (2681).\n- Closing areas to all non-towed (static) fishing gears was associated with higher overall shark abundance when sampled with longlines (but not with gillnets) and greater length for two of five shark species/groups compared to areas permitting commercial gillnets (2670).\n- Prohibiting commercial fishing was associated with different benthic invertebrate community composition relative to fished areas; no change in overall invertebrate species richness in one case; greater overall invertebrate abundance in closed areas in two cases, with biomass higher in one and similar in another; no difference in lobster abundance after up to two years; and greater biological production from invertebrates where trawling and dredging had been excluded for 28 years (2097).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2678",
